SIMPLE: filler
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Filler
<hw>Fill"er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One who,
or that which, fills; something used for filling.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>'T is mere <qex>filler</qex>, to stop a vacancy in the
hexameter.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They have six diggers to four <qex>fillers</qex>, so as to keep
the <qex>fillers</qex> always at work.</q>
<rj><qau>Mortimer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Paint.)</fld> <def>A composition, as of powdered
silica and oil, used to fill the pores and grain of wood before applying
paint, varnish, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Forestry)</fld> <def>Any standing tree or standard
higher than the surrounding coppice in the form of forest known as
<membof>coppice under standards</membof>. Chiefly used in the
<pluf>pl.</pluf></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Filler</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Filler
<hw>Fill"er</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From 1st <er>Fill</er>.]</ety>
<def>A thill horse.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fillet</ent>⟦br⟧
